  "text": "ArangoDB's authentication and authorization infrastructure is composed of several key components:\n\n1. **Authentication Handlers**\n   - `arangod/Auth/Handler.h` defines the abstract `Handler` interface for implementing different authentication methods (e.g., Basic, JWT).\n   - `arangod/RestHandler/RestAuthHandler.h/cpp` implements the `RestAuthHandler` class which handles the `/_open/auth` endpoint. It provides the `generateJwt()` method to create JWT tokens for authenticated users.\n\n2. **JWT Token Validation**\n   - `arangod/Auth/TokenCache.h/cpp` is the core JWT validation component. The `TokenCache` class implements:\n     - `checkAuthenticationJWT()`: Main JWT validation method\n     - `validateJwtBody()`: Parses and validates JWT body claims\n     - `validateJwtHMAC256Signature()`: Validates HMAC-SHA256 signatures\n     - `validateJwtES256Signature()`: Validates ECDSA-SHA256 signatures\n   - The class also manages JWT secrets (active and passive) and maintains an LRU cache for validated tokens.\n\n3. **User Management**\n   - `arangod/Auth/UserManager.h` defines the `UserManager` interface for accessing users and their permissions stored in `_system/_users`.\n   - `arangod/Auth/UserManagerImpl.cpp/h` provides the concrete implementation including user loading, caching, and permission resolution.\n   - `arangod/Auth/User.h/cpp` defines the `User` class that represents a user entry with:\n     - Password verification: `User::checkPassword()`\n     - Access token checking: `User::checkAccessToken()`\n     - Permission management for databases and collections\n\n4. **Authorization Context**\n   - `arangod/Utils/ExecContext.h` defines the `ExecContext` class which carries execution context information:\n     - `ExecContext::current()`: Returns the current execution context with user information\n     - `ExecContext::isSuperuser()`: Checks if user has admin privileges\n     - `ExecContext::isAdminUser()`: Checks admin user status\n     - Stores system and database-level authorization (RW, RO, or NONE)\n\n5. **User Management REST API**\n   - `arangod/RestHandler/RestUsersHandler.h/cpp` implements the `RestUsersHandler` class which serves the `/_api/user` endpoint for user management operations (GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE).\n\n6. **Access Token Management**\n   - `arangod/RestHandler/RestAccessTokenHandler.h/cpp` implements the `RestAccessTokenHandler` class for managing user access tokens:\n     - `createAccessToken()`: Creates new access tokens\n     - `deleteAccessToken()`: Deletes tokens\n     - `showAccessTokens()`: Lists user tokens\n\n7. **Configuration and Startup Options**\n   - `arangod/GeneralServer/AuthenticationFeature.h/cpp` implements the `AuthenticationFeature` class which:\n     - Manages authentication configuration via `AuthenticationOptions`\n     - Provides the `collectOptions()` method to register startup options\n     - Key options include `--server.authentication`, `--server.session-timeout`, `--auth.minimal-jwt-expiry-time`, `--auth.maximal-jwt-expiry-time`\n     - Implements `loadJwtSecretsFromFile()` and `loadJwtSecretFolder()` for loading JWT secrets\n   - `arangod/GeneralServer/AuthenticationOptions.h` defines the `AuthenticationOptions` struct with default settings:\n     - `authenticationUnixSockets = true` (enabled)\n     - `authenticationSystemOnly = true` (system-only authentication)\n     - `sessionTimeout = 3600.0` seconds (1 hour)\n     - `minimalJwtExpiryTime = 10.0` seconds\n     - `maximalJwtExpiryTime = 3600.0` seconds\n     - Support for both HMAC and ES256 JWT signing\n\nThe authentication flow: User credentials are submitted to `RestAuthHandler` → validated via `TokenCache::checkAuthenticationJWT()` or `UserManager::checkCredentials()` → on success, a JWT token is generated and cached → subsequent requests include the token in the Authorization header → the token is validated and an `ExecContext` is created with appropriate permission levels for the user."
}

